Note:
==============================================================================
TimeSpan - Bounded Interval Primitive + Allen's Interval Algebra
==============================================================================

A TimeSpan represents a bounded interval on the monotonic time line, anchored
by a (start_instant, end_instant) pair where each endpoint is an Instant
(nanoseconds since the OS monotonic epoch). Inclusivity flags determine
whether each endpoint belongs to the interval: by default a TimeSpan is
half-open [start, end), matching the conventions of Java java.time intervals
and the C++ std::chrono::time_point ranges.

This module ALSO re-exports the Duration API under TimeSpan-style names so
the legacy duration-aliased call sites continue to compile. The two surfaces
are independent:

  * Duration-style API: time_span_from_seconds(n), time_span_add(a, b, r),
    time_span_to_nanoseconds(t) - operates on signed nanosecond magnitudes
    backed by duration.runa buffers.

  * Interval API: time_span_create(start, end), span_overlaps(A, B),
    span_intersect(A, B) - operates on TimeSpan struct buffers containing
    two Instant endpoints plus inclusivity flags.

The Allen interval algebra implemented here follows Allen 1983 ("Maintaining
knowledge about temporal intervals", Communications of the ACM 26(11):832-843).
The 13 base relations partition the space of ordered pairs of bounded intervals
into mutually exclusive cases. For half-open and open intervals the "meets"
relation degenerates to "before" because the shared boundary point does not
belong to both intervals; this module documents the precise semantics in each
predicate.

Storage layout (32 bytes):
  offset  0 .. 8   : start_instant (Integer nanoseconds)
  offset  8 .. 16  : end_instant   (Integer nanoseconds)
  offset 16 .. 24  : is_inclusive_start (Integer flag, 0 or 1)
  offset 24 .. 32  : is_inclusive_end   (Integer flag, 0 or 1)

References:
  Allen 1983, Communications of the ACM 26(11):832-843
  Java java.time interval semantics (JSR-310)
  .NET System.TimeSpan
  C++ std::chrono::duration (ISO/IEC 14882 §29.5.1)
==============================================================================
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/time/duration.runa" as DurationModule
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/time/instant.runa" as InstantModule
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as MemoryCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant TIME_SPAN_OK as Integer is 0
Constant TIME_SPAN_ERR_NULL as Integer is -1
Constant TIME_SPAN_ERR_DIVIDE_BY_ZERO as Integer is -2
Constant TIME_SPAN_ERR_DISJOINT as Integer is -3
Constant TIME_SPAN_ERR_EMPTY as Integer is -4

Note: TimeSpan struct layout
Constant TIME_SPAN_STRUCT_SIZE as Integer is 32
Constant TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET as Integer is 0
Constant TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET as Integer is 8
Constant TIME_SPAN_INCL_START_OFFSET as Integer is 16
Constant TIME_SPAN_INCL_END_OFFSET as Integer is 24

Note: Inclusivity flag values
Constant TIME_SPAN_INCLUSIVE as Integer is 1
Constant TIME_SPAN_EXCLUSIVE as Integer is 0

