Note: ============================================================================
Note: Bounded-interval TimeSpan struct API
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "time_span_create" takes start as Integer, end_value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Constructs a half-open TimeSpan [start, end_value) using the supplied
    Instants (each an Integer nanosecond reading as defined by instant.runa).
    The half-open convention is the default because it composes cleanly
    under union and complement: the right endpoint of one interval may be
    the left endpoint of the next without producing a double-counted point.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Allocates a 32-byte struct on the owned heap and writes the four fields
    via memory_set_int64. The inclusivity flags are set to (1, 0) which
    encodes half-open semantics. Returns 0 on allocation failure.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One small heap allocation plus four 8-byte stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller takes ownership of the returned pointer and must release it via
    time_span_destroy.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let span_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with TIME_SPAN_STRUCT_SIZE
    If span_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let r1 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with span_ptr, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET, start
    Let r2 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with span_ptr, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET, end_value
    Let r3 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with span_ptr, TIME_SPAN_INCL_START_OFFSET, TIME_SPAN_INCLUSIVE
    Let r4 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with span_ptr, TIME_SPAN_INCL_END_OFFSET, TIME_SPAN_EXCLUSIVE
    Return span_ptr
End Process

Process called "time_span_create_closed" takes start as Integer, end_value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Constructs a closed TimeSpan [start, end_value]. Both endpoints belong
    to the interval. Closed intervals are the natural domain of Allen's
    original algebra; "meets" between two closed intervals A and B requires
    A.end == B.start and they share that single point.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Same allocation pattern as time_span_create but writes (1, 1) for the
    inclusivity flags.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One alloc plus four stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns the returned pointer.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let span_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with TIME_SPAN_STRUCT_SIZE
    If span_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let r1 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with span_ptr, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET, start
    Let r2 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with span_ptr, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET, end_value
    Let r3 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with span_ptr, TIME_SPAN_INCL_START_OFFSET, TIME_SPAN_INCLUSIVE
    Let r4 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with span_ptr, TIME_SPAN_INCL_END_OFFSET, TIME_SPAN_INCLUSIVE
    Return span_ptr
End Process

Process called "time_span_create_open" takes start as Integer, end_value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Constructs an open TimeSpan (start, end_value). Neither endpoint belongs
    to the interval. Used for "strictly between" queries in scheduling and
    constraint solving.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Same allocation pattern as time_span_create but writes (0, 0) for the
    inclusivity flags.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One alloc plus four stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns the returned pointer.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let span_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with TIME_SPAN_STRUCT_SIZE
    If span_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let r1 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with span_ptr, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET, start
    Let r2 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with span_ptr, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET, end_value
    Let r3 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with span_ptr, TIME_SPAN_INCL_START_OFFSET, TIME_SPAN_EXCLUSIVE
    Let r4 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with span_ptr, TIME_SPAN_INCL_END_OFFSET, TIME_SPAN_EXCLUSIVE
    Return span_ptr
End Process

Process called "time_span_from_duration" takes start as Integer, duration_ns as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Constructs a half-open TimeSpan [start, start + duration_ns). The duration
    is expressed as a signed nanosecond count (the natural output of
    duration_to_nanoseconds), so the caller need not allocate a Duration
    buffer for the common "anchor + length" pattern.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Computes end = start + duration_ns by integer addition (Instant nanoseconds
    fit in the 292-year monotonic window so no overflow check is required),
    then delegates to time_span_create.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One addition plus the cost of time_span_create.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns the returned pointer. A negative duration_ns produces an
    interval whose end precedes its start; downstream predicates treat this
    as empty via time_span_is_empty.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let end_value be start plus duration_ns
    Return proc time_span_create with start, end_value
End Process

Process called "time_span_destroy" takes span as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Releases a TimeSpan struct allocated by any of the time_span_create
    constructors or by span_intersect / span_union.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Forwards to Layout.deallocate; a null pointer is a no-op consistent with
    the rest of the primitive layer.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single tier-3 free.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller must not retain dangling references to the freed pointer.
    @End Security_Scope
    If span is equal to 0:
        Return TIME_SPAN_OK
    End If
    Let dummy be proc deallocate from Layout with span
    Return TIME_SPAN_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Accessors
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "time_span_start" takes span as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the start Instant of the interval.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Reads the 8-byte field at TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One memory load.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read of caller-owned memory; null pointer returns 0 to match the
    "no-op on null" convention used by the rest of the primitive layer.
    @End Security_Scope
    If span is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with span, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
End Process

Process called "time_span_end" takes span as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the end Instant of the interval.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
