    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with span, TIME_SPAN_INCL_START_OFFSET
End Process

Process called "time_span_is_inclusive_end" takes span as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns 1 iff the end endpoint belongs to the interval.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Reads the inclusivity flag at TIME_SPAN_INCL_END_OFFSET.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One memory load.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read of caller-owned memory; null pointer returns 0.
    @End Security_Scope
    If span is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with span, TIME_SPAN_INCL_END_OFFSET
End Process

Process called "time_span_duration" takes span as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the signed nanosecond length end - start. For a well-formed
    interval (start <= end) this is non-negative; for a reversed interval
    it is negative, matching POSIX timersub conventions.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Loads both endpoints and returns end - start. Inclusivity does not
    affect duration; a closed [0, 5] and a half-open [0, 5) both have
    length 5 nanoseconds, since duration is a continuous measure and
    individual nanosecond endpoints carry no measurable extent.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two loads plus one subtraction.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read of caller-owned memory; null pointer returns 0.
    @End Security_Scope
    If span is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let start_value be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with span, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let end_value be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with span, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    Return end_value minus start_value
End Process

Process called "time_span_is_empty" takes span as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    An interval is empty iff it contains no points. The exact criterion
    depends on inclusivity:
      * Closed [a, b]: empty iff a > b
      * Half-open [a, b) or (a, b]: empty iff a >= b
      * Open (a, b): empty iff a + 1 > b, which for integer nanoseconds
        reduces to a >= b (the interval (n, n+1) of integers is empty
        because there is no integer strictly between n and n+1).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Loads both endpoints and the inclusivity flags, then applies the
    appropriate predicate. For mixed inclusivity (one side closed, one
    open) the half-open rule applies.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Four loads plus at most two compares.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Read of caller-owned memory; null pointer returns 1 (a null interval
    is treated as empty for safe-default reasoning).
    @End Security_Scope
    If span is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let start_value be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with span, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let end_value be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with span, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    Let incl_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with span, TIME_SPAN_INCL_START_OFFSET
    Let incl_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with span, TIME_SPAN_INCL_END_OFFSET
    Note: Closed on both sides: empty iff start > end.
    If incl_start is equal to 1:
        If incl_end is equal to 1:
            If start_value is greater than end_value:
                Return 1
            End If
            Return 0
        End If
    End If
    Note: All other inclusivity combinations: empty iff start >= end.
    If start_value is greater than end_value:
        Return 1
    End If
    If start_value is equal to end_value:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
Allen's Interval Algebra - 13 Base Relations
============================================================================

Reference: Allen, J. F. (1983). Maintaining knowledge about temporal
intervals. Communications of the ACM, 26(11), 832-843.

The 13 relations form a jointly exhaustive and mutually exclusive
partition of the space of ordered pairs of non-empty bounded intervals.
For closed intervals the semantics in the paper are exact. For
half-open and open intervals "meets" degenerates: if A.end == B.start
but the shared point belongs to neither interval, A and B do not
actually touch, so meets reduces to before. This implementation
compares the raw endpoint values; callers reasoning about half-open
intervals should remember that A and B with A.end == B.start are
classified here as "meets" by endpoint comparison even though no
shared instant exists. For mathematical exactness in such cases,
use closed intervals via time_span_create_closed.
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "span_before" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allen relation 1: A precedes B with a strict gap. A.end < B.start.
    Mutually exclusive with all other relations.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Single signed compare on the end Instant of A versus the start Instant
    of B.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two loads plus one compare.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function over caller-owned memory; null inputs return 0
    (no relation can be established).
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let a_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    Let b_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    If a_end is less than b_start:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "span_meets" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allen relation 2: A ends exactly when B begins. A.end == B.start.
    For closed intervals A and B literally share the boundary point; for
    half-open / open intervals the boundary belongs to neither and the
    intervals are arithmetically adjacent without overlapping.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Single equality test on A.end versus B.start.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two loads plus one compare.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function; null inputs return 0.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let a_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    Let b_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    If a_end is equal to b_start:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "span_overlaps" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allen relation 3: partial overlap where A starts first.
    A.start < B.start AND A.end > B.start AND A.end < B.end.
    The middle conjunct excludes the "meets" case; the rightmost conjunct
    excludes "finished_by" and "contains".
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Loads four endpoints and applies the three-way conjunction.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Four loads plus three signed compares; short-circuits on the first
    falsified clause.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function; null inputs return 0.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let a_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let a_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    Let b_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let b_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    If a_start is less than b_start:
        If a_end is greater than b_start:
            If a_end is less than b_end:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "span_finished_by" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allen relation 4: B finishes A. A.start < B.start AND A.end == B.end.
    Inverse of "finishes": A is the longer interval and B nests inside A
    sharing the right endpoint.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Loads four endpoints and tests the two-clause conjunction.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Four loads plus two compares.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function; null inputs return 0.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let a_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let a_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    Let b_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let b_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    If a_start is less than b_start:
        If a_end is equal to b_end:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "span_contains" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allen relation 5: A strictly contains B. A.start < B.start AND A.end > B.end.
    Both endpoints of B lie strictly inside A.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Loads four endpoints and tests the two-clause conjunction.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Four loads plus two compares.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function; null inputs return 0.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let a_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let a_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    Let b_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let b_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    If a_start is less than b_start:
        If a_end is greater than b_end:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "span_starts" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allen relation 6: A and B share the start, A is the shorter.
    A.start == B.start AND A.end < B.end.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Loads four endpoints and tests the two-clause conjunction.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Four loads plus two compares.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function; null inputs return 0.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let a_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let a_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    Let b_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let b_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    If a_start is equal to b_start:
        If a_end is less than b_end:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "span_equals" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allen relation 7: A and B coincide. A.start == B.start AND A.end == B.end.
    This compares endpoint values only; two intervals with identical endpoints
    but different inclusivity flags are reported as equal by this predicate
    because Allen's algebra is defined on closed intervals where inclusivity
    is implicit.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Loads four endpoints and tests both equalities.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Four loads plus two compares.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function; null inputs return 0.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let a_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let a_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    Let b_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let b_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    If a_start is equal to b_start:
        If a_end is equal to b_end:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "span_started_by" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allen relation 8: inverse of "starts". A and B share the start, A is
    the longer. A.start == B.start AND A.end > B.end.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Loads four endpoints and tests the two-clause conjunction.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Four loads plus two compares.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function; null inputs return 0.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let a_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let a_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    Let b_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let b_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    If a_start is equal to b_start:
        If a_end is greater than b_end:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "span_during" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allen relation 9: A is strictly inside B.
    A.start > B.start AND A.end < B.end.
    Inverse of "contains".
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Loads four endpoints and tests the two-clause conjunction.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Four loads plus two compares.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function; null inputs return 0.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let a_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let a_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    Let b_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let b_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    If a_start is greater than b_start:
        If a_end is less than b_end:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "span_finishes" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allen relation 10: A and B share the end, A is the shorter.
    A.start > B.start AND A.end == B.end.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Loads four endpoints and tests the two-clause conjunction.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Four loads plus two compares.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function; null inputs return 0.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let a_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let a_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    Let b_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let b_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    If a_start is greater than b_start:
        If a_end is equal to b_end:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "span_overlapped_by" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allen relation 11: B partially overlaps A from the left.
    A.start > B.start AND A.start < B.end AND A.end > B.end.
    Inverse of "overlaps".
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Loads four endpoints and applies the three-way conjunction.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Four loads plus three signed compares.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function; null inputs return 0.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let a_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let a_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    Let b_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let b_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    If a_start is greater than b_start:
        If a_start is less than b_end:
            If a_end is greater than b_end:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "span_met_by" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allen relation 12: B ends exactly when A begins. A.start == B.end.
    Inverse of "meets".
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Single equality test on A.start versus B.end.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two loads plus one compare.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function; null inputs return 0.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let a_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let b_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    If a_start is equal to b_end:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "span_after" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allen relation 13: A follows B with a strict gap. A.start > B.end.
    Inverse of "before".
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Single signed compare on the start Instant of A versus the end Instant
    of B.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two loads plus one compare.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function; null inputs return 0.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let a_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let b_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    If a_start is greater than b_end:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Higher-level interval operations
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "span_contains_instant" takes span as Integer, instant_ns as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns 1 iff the supplied Instant belongs to the interval, honouring
    the inclusivity flags. For closed [a, b]: a <= x <= b. For half-open
    [a, b): a <= x < b. For half-open (a, b]: a < x <= b. For open (a, b):
    a < x < b.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Loads the two endpoints and the two inclusivity flags, then selects
    the correct comparison form for each side. The left compare uses
    "<=" when the start is inclusive and "<" when exclusive; symmetrically
    for the right.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Four loads plus two compares.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function; null span returns 0.
    @End Security_Scope
    If span is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let start_value be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with span, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let end_value be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with span, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    Let incl_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with span, TIME_SPAN_INCL_START_OFFSET
    Let incl_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with span, TIME_SPAN_INCL_END_OFFSET
    Note: Left boundary check.
    If incl_start is equal to 1:
        If instant_ns is less than start_value:
            Return 0
        End If
    Otherwise:
        If instant_ns is less than start_value:
            Return 0
        End If
        If instant_ns is equal to start_value:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If
    Note: Right boundary check.
    If incl_end is equal to 1:
        If instant_ns is greater than end_value:
            Return 0
        End If
    Otherwise:
        If instant_ns is greater than end_value:
            Return 0
        End If
        If instant_ns is equal to end_value:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "span_overlaps_any" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns 1 iff A and B share at least one moment. Equivalent to the
    disjunction of all Allen relations except "before", "after", and (for
    half-open / open intervals) "meets" / "met_by". The fast endpoint test
    is: A.start < B.end AND A.end > B.start (interpreted as <= when the
    matching side of either interval is inclusive).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Loads four endpoints plus four inclusivity flags. The test is
    "not (A entirely before B) AND not (B entirely before A)".
    A is entirely before B iff A.end < B.start, or A.end == B.start with
    at least one of A.end exclusive or B.start exclusive. Symmetric for
    the other direction.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Eight loads plus at most four compares. The two empty-interval guards
    short-circuit when either side has zero extent.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function; null inputs return 0.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let a_empty be proc time_span_is_empty with a
    If a_empty is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let b_empty be proc time_span_is_empty with b
    If b_empty is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let a_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let a_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    Let b_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let b_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    Let a_incl_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_INCL_END_OFFSET
    Let b_incl_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_INCL_START_OFFSET
    Let a_incl_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_INCL_START_OFFSET
    Let b_incl_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_INCL_END_OFFSET
    Note: A is entirely before B iff a_end < b_start, or a_end == b_start with either side exclusive.
    If a_end is less than b_start:
        Return 0
    End If
    If a_end is equal to b_start:
        If a_incl_end is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If
        If b_incl_start is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If
    Note: B is entirely before A iff b_end < a_start, or b_end == a_start with either side exclusive.
    If b_end is less than a_start:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b_end is equal to a_start:
        If b_incl_end is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If
        If a_incl_start is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "span_intersect" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns a freshly allocated TimeSpan representing A intersect B, or 0
    when A and B share no moment. The result has start = max(A.start, B.start)
    and end = min(A.end, B.end). The intersection inclusivity at each side
    is the AND of the contributing flags: a point belongs to the intersection
    iff it belongs to both inputs.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    First checks span_overlaps_any to short-circuit the disjoint case.
    Then computes the intersection endpoints and the AND'd inclusivity
    flags, allocates a new TimeSpan struct, and writes all four fields.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One allocation plus a constant number of loads and stores. The
    overlap check is amortised; for callers who have already established
    overlap the cost is dominated by the allocation.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns the returned pointer and must release it via
    time_span_destroy.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let overlap be proc span_overlaps_any with a, b
    If overlap is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let a_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let a_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    Let b_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let b_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    Let a_incl_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_INCL_START_OFFSET
    Let a_incl_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_INCL_END_OFFSET
    Let b_incl_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_INCL_START_OFFSET
    Let b_incl_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_INCL_END_OFFSET
    Note: Result start = max(starts); inclusivity is the AND iff endpoints tie, otherwise inherits from the winning side.
    Let new_start be a_start
    Let new_incl_start be a_incl_start
    If b_start is greater than a_start:
        Set new_start to b_start
        Set new_incl_start to b_incl_start
    End If
    If a_start is equal to b_start:
        Note: Tie: a point is in both iff both flags say so.
        If a_incl_start is equal to 1:
            If b_incl_start is equal to 1:
                Set new_incl_start to 1
            Otherwise:
                Set new_incl_start to 0
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Set new_incl_start to 0
        End If
    End If
    Note: Result end = min(ends); symmetric rule on inclusivity.
    Let new_end be a_end
    Let new_incl_end be a_incl_end
    If b_end is less than a_end:
        Set new_end to b_end
        Set new_incl_end to b_incl_end
    End If
    If a_end is equal to b_end:
        If a_incl_end is equal to 1:
            If b_incl_end is equal to 1:
                Set new_incl_end to 1
            Otherwise:
                Set new_incl_end to 0
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Set new_incl_end to 0
        End If
    End If
    Let span_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with TIME_SPAN_STRUCT_SIZE
    If span_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let w1 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with span_ptr, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET, new_start
    Let w2 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with span_ptr, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET, new_end
    Let w3 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with span_ptr, TIME_SPAN_INCL_START_OFFSET, new_incl_start
    Let w4 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with span_ptr, TIME_SPAN_INCL_END_OFFSET, new_incl_end
    Return span_ptr
End Process

Process called "span_union" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns a freshly allocated TimeSpan representing A union B when the
    union is a single connected interval, or 0 when A and B are disjoint
    (the union would not be a single TimeSpan). Two intervals are considered
    "connected" here if they overlap or share a boundary point that belongs
    to at least one of them. The result has start = min(starts) and end =
    max(ends); inclusivity at each side is the OR of the contributing flags:
    a point belongs to the union iff it belongs to either input.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Tests connectivity by checking span_overlaps_any first; for adjacent
    half-open / open intervals that are not considered overlapping (e.g.
    [0, 5) and [5, 10)), an extra equality + inclusivity check recovers
    the "touches" case where at least one side claims the shared boundary.
    Then computes the union endpoints and OR'd inclusivity flags and
    allocates a new struct.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One allocation plus a constant number of loads and stores. Disjoint
    short-circuit avoids the alloc entirely.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns the returned pointer.
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let a_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let a_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    Let b_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let b_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    Let a_incl_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_INCL_START_OFFSET
    Let a_incl_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_INCL_END_OFFSET
    Let b_incl_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_INCL_START_OFFSET
    Let b_incl_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with b, TIME_SPAN_INCL_END_OFFSET
    Note: Connectivity check: overlap OR touching at a boundary that at least one side claims.
    Let connected be 0
    Let overlap be proc span_overlaps_any with a, b
    If overlap is equal to 1:
        Set connected to 1
    End If
    If connected is equal to 0:
        If a_end is equal to b_start:
            If a_incl_end is equal to 1:
                Set connected to 1
            End If
            If b_incl_start is equal to 1:
                Set connected to 1
            End If
        End If
    End If
    If connected is equal to 0:
        If b_end is equal to a_start:
            If b_incl_end is equal to 1:
                Set connected to 1
            End If
            If a_incl_start is equal to 1:
                Set connected to 1
            End If
        End If
    End If
    If connected is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Note: Result start = min(starts); inclusivity OR on tie, otherwise inherits.
    Let new_start be a_start
    Let new_incl_start be a_incl_start
    If b_start is less than a_start:
        Set new_start to b_start
        Set new_incl_start to b_incl_start
    End If
    If a_start is equal to b_start:
        Set new_incl_start to 0
        If a_incl_start is equal to 1:
            Set new_incl_start to 1
        End If
        If b_incl_start is equal to 1:
            Set new_incl_start to 1
        End If
    End If
    Note: Result end = max(ends); symmetric OR rule.
    Let new_end be a_end
    Let new_incl_end be a_incl_end
    If b_end is greater than a_end:
        Set new_end to b_end
        Set new_incl_end to b_incl_end
    End If
    If a_end is equal to b_end:
        Set new_incl_end to 0
        If a_incl_end is equal to 1:
            Set new_incl_end to 1
        End If
        If b_incl_end is equal to 1:
            Set new_incl_end to 1
        End If
    End If
    Let span_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with TIME_SPAN_STRUCT_SIZE
    If span_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let w1 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with span_ptr, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET, new_start
    Let w2 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with span_ptr, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET, new_end
    Let w3 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with span_ptr, TIME_SPAN_INCL_START_OFFSET, new_incl_start
    Let w4 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with span_ptr, TIME_SPAN_INCL_END_OFFSET, new_incl_end
    Return span_ptr
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
Complement
============================================================================

span_complement returns its result through three out-pointers because
the Runa primitive layer does not yet expose a List[Pointer] type and
the complement can produce 0, 1, or 2 fragments depending on whether
A coincides with the universe, touches one edge, or sits strictly
inside. The integer return value reports the fragment count.
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "span_complement" takes a as Integer, universe as Integer, out_first as Integer, out_second as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the universe-relative complement of A: the set of points in
    universe that are NOT in A. Writes 0, 1, or 2 freshly allocated
    TimeSpan pointers into the two out-pointer cells and returns the
    fragment count. The complement of A relative to a universe U is:
      * empty (return 0)         when A coincides with U
      * one interval (return 1)  when A shares exactly one endpoint with U
      * two intervals (return 2) when A is strictly inside U
    For half-open universe semantics the algorithm uses endpoint equality
    plus inclusivity matching to decide coincidence.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    The complement of A inside U decomposes into the prefix [U.start, A.start)
    and the suffix (A.end, U.end] (with inclusivity adjusted by the rule
    "a point is in the complement iff it is in U and not in A"). The prefix
    is non-empty when U.start < A.start or when the endpoints coincide and
    the inclusivity flags differ; symmetric for the suffix. Each non-empty
    fragment is allocated via time_span_create_open / time_span_create_closed
    variants depending on the recovered inclusivity flags.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Up to two allocations plus a constant number of loads.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns any non-zero pointers written into out_first / out_second
    and must release them via time_span_destroy. The out_first / out_second
    cells must be valid 8-byte memory locations; null cells are tolerated
    (the corresponding fragment is suppressed and not written, but is still
    counted in the return value if logically present, which would leak the
    allocation - callers MUST pass valid cells).
    @End Security_Scope
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If universe is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let a_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let a_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    Let a_incl_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_INCL_START_OFFSET
    Let a_incl_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with a, TIME_SPAN_INCL_END_OFFSET
    Let u_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with universe, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET
    Let u_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with universe, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET
    Let u_incl_start be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with universe, TIME_SPAN_INCL_START_OFFSET
    Let u_incl_end be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with universe, TIME_SPAN_INCL_END_OFFSET
    Note: Determine prefix [U.start, A.start) existence.
    Let prefix_exists be 0
    If u_start is less than a_start:
        Set prefix_exists to 1
    End If
    If u_start is equal to a_start:
        Note: Tie. Prefix is the single point u_start iff it is in U but not A.
        If u_incl_start is equal to 1:
            If a_incl_start is equal to 0:
                Set prefix_exists to 1
            End If
        End If
    End If
    Note: Determine suffix (A.end, U.end] existence.
    Let suffix_exists be 0
    If a_end is less than u_end:
        Set suffix_exists to 1
    End If
    If a_end is equal to u_end:
        Note: Tie. Suffix is the single point u_end iff it is in U but not A.
        If u_incl_end is equal to 1:
            If a_incl_end is equal to 0:
                Set suffix_exists to 1
            End If
        End If
    End If
    Let count be 0
    If prefix_exists is equal to 1:
        Let pref_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with TIME_SPAN_STRUCT_SIZE
        If pref_ptr is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let p1 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with pref_ptr, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET, u_start
        Let p2 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with pref_ptr, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET, a_start
        Let p3 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with pref_ptr, TIME_SPAN_INCL_START_OFFSET, u_incl_start
        Note: Prefix end is the negation of A's start inclusivity: a point at A.start belongs to A iff a_incl_start, hence does NOT belong to complement iff a_incl_start.
        Let pref_end_incl be 1
        If a_incl_start is equal to 1:
            Set pref_end_incl to 0
        End If
        Let p4 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with pref_ptr, TIME_SPAN_INCL_END_OFFSET, pref_end_incl
        Let s1 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_first, 0, pref_ptr
        Set count to count plus 1
    End If
    If suffix_exists is equal to 1:
        Let suf_ptr be proc allocate from Layout with TIME_SPAN_STRUCT_SIZE
        If suf_ptr is equal to 0:
            Return count
        End If
        Let s_start be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with suf_ptr, TIME_SPAN_START_OFFSET, a_end
        Let s_end be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with suf_ptr, TIME_SPAN_END_OFFSET, u_end
        Note: Suffix start inclusivity is the negation of A.end inclusivity.
        Let suf_start_incl be 1
        If a_incl_end is equal to 1:
            Set suf_start_incl to 0
        End If
        Let s_incl_s be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with suf_ptr, TIME_SPAN_INCL_START_OFFSET, suf_start_incl
        Let s_incl_e be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with suf_ptr, TIME_SPAN_INCL_END_OFFSET, u_incl_end
        Note: Route to out_first when no prefix was produced, otherwise to out_second.
        If count is equal to 0:
            Let r1 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_first, 0, suf_ptr
        Otherwise:
            Let r2 be proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with out_second, 0, suf_ptr
        End If
        Set count to count plus 1
    End If
    Return count
End Process
